Winter books open! Use the link in my bio “booking form.” This includes the rest of December, Jan, and Feb in nyc. Winter is a fantastic time to be tattooed as you don’t risk sun exposure and can keep your healing tattoo covered.
.
If you haven’t been tattooed by me, or been tattooed at all - I’m very easy to work with! I love every moment of tattooing so I’m able to get excited about almost anything. My only goal is you walking away profoundly happy - we can edit whatever we need to, as long as you like, to fit it your desires and body. Try not to worry about coming with a sufficiently artsy or intellectual subject matter! There’s beauty to be found in all things and I find joy in hunting for it. 
.
.

💐 Freshly picked! Ive still got some spots left in the winter if any of these warm your heart💫

Blue fire plant growth. This was a piece of flash that we recolored to her liking and fit to echo her existing tattoo. The floral flash I provide are each a discrete little language and *that* is what I’m selling you. While we can always just make a piece straight off the wall, all of my floral can be reformed, reshaped, extended, recolored, or replicated. Like the shapes and drawing elements of one piece, but the color scheme of another? Cool! That takes like 3 minutes on an iPad and opens up a huuuuge world of options. Enjoy! 
.
Also: you should read/listen to Children of Time by Adrian Tchaikovsky. It’s sci-fi but half of it is from the pov of a hyper-intelligent spider society that is so tenderly written that if it doesn’t make you feel deep empathy for all forms of intelligence then shame on you lol

Why are plants cool? Here’s how photosynthesis works: photons (quantum particles of light) hits the plant. The plant converts each photon into something called an exciton. Here’s where it gets spooky. Ok, so how do we convert raw light into chemical nutrients to sustain the plant? How does the light know where to go to feed it? Excitons use the quantum nature of reality itself. Imagine each bit of food for the plant steps up to a series of doors. One is labeled “petals”, another is “bulb”, another is “stamen”, and so on, but also each cell within each of those superstructures. How does that food get to where it needs to go? Isn’t the point to trap the kinetic energy of the photon? Won’t it lose energy if it has to check against each cell of the plant in sequence to see if it’s needed? Rather than check each door to see if it’s needed, the exciton *checks all of the doors simultaneously*. It harnesses its own quantum superposition to see where it’s needed instantly, then goes there. Voila! If that excites you, wait till you hear about the human brain!
